"{\"uid\": \"salon.com-2024-08-10-olympic-comebacks\", \"text\": \"If theParis Olympicshad a theme, it would be \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ccomeback.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d The sense of normalcy after Tokyo\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s largely amended agenda in 2021, devoid of fans and laced with stringent pandemic-era restrictions.Celine Dion\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s triumphant return to the stage, as she closed out theopening ceremonywith a glittering and emotional rendition of Edith Piaf's \\\"Hymne \\u00c3\\u00a0 l\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099amour.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Public health and artful performances aside, however, these Olympics marked the culmination of comeback campaigns for some of Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s most prominent athletes.  Simone Biles, Sunisa Lee, Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri Richardson. Two gymnasts and a sprinter, each of whom has held a central role in our domestic success at the Olympics thus far (the U.S. currently leads with the most gold medals won) and in drawing a global audience to their screens. For all that distinguishes them athletically, there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s one commonality that Biles, Lee and Richardson share in earnest \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 their redemption tour.  Before they were Olympians, they were Simone, Sunisa and Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri.  Currently, each of these women is at the height of their physical performance, further cementing themselves as exemplars of their respective sports through their Olympic efforts. But how do we conceptualize them outside of this mold? Before the aerials, the back handsprings, the 100-meter dashes and relay handoffs, these seemingly otherworldly talents are still regular people. And regular people, as anyone can attest, are saddled with issues outside of their professional lives that still directly affect them. We can look then, to this trio's comeback stories and successes in Paris as a reminder that we should view people holistically, not merely through the lens of their chosen disciplines or what they most excel at.\\u00c2  Related  In Salon's recentinterviewfor the Netflix documentary, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSimone Biles: Rising,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d director Katie Walsh shared that Biles felt it was pivotal to \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cgive people a window into her entire self.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe all see her on the floor as the G.O.A.T. and the greatest ever. But we all do not get to see and have the privilege of getting to know Simone, the human being,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Walsh said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd I know for her, she wants to be looked at and viewed as a full human and not just this amazing gymnast you have come to really expect to be perfect at all times.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Given that Biles, who recently becamethe most decorated American gymnast of all time, is widely regarded as an uncontested talent in the sport, a comeback is not necessarily something that fans might have expected of her. What would she have to return to if she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s already at the top?  Walsh\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s sentiments \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 and the documentary more broadly \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 follow a debilitating era in the Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 history in gymnastics. After suffering a bout of the\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ctwisties,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2\\u00a0a disorienting sensation that unmoored Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 body from her mind in Tokyo, she elected to withdraw from the Games. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have to focus on my mental health,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Biles said at the time,per the BBC.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t trust myself as much anymore.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Simone Biles Rising (Netflix)Evidently, neither did a number of others. Rather than being lauded for her bravery (and numerous medals from the Rio Games in 2016), her decision was widely panned by online critics who scrutinized her \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cabandonment\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d of her teammates. Media mudslinging abounded on various social media platforms. Journalist Tim Constantine swiftly authored anop-ed for The Washington Timestitled, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSimone Biles is no hero. She is a quitter.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Coupled with her 2021testimonybefore the U.S. Senate regarding sexual abuse she and other members of USA Gymnastics endured by former team doctor, Larry Nassar, Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 mental health quickly deteriorated.\\u00c2  Three years later, Biles has flipped the script on the haters, outperforming even herself with three gold medals \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 all-around team, all-around individual, and vault \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 and one silver \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 for the floor event \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 to add to her collection. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBeing in a good mental spot, seeing my therapist every Thursday is kind of religious for me. So that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s why I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m here today,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d the phenomtold NBCin a June interview, openly attributing consistent mental care to her sparkling return.\\u00c2  Many Americans can and should look to Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 embracement of mental health services for inspiration. A 2021reportfrom the Mental Health Million Project found that 45 percent of individuals in the U.S. suffering from a clinical mental problem do not seek help. While the reasons behind why people forgo treatment are varied and often subjective, America\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s cultural dismissal of therapy and general obstinance about prioritizing mental health gives credence to the intense backlash Biles faced post-Tokyo.\\u00c2  For Lee, the issues plaguing her physical health found a nexus with her mental state. Her path to the Paris Games was stymied by a diagnosis in 2022. A chronic, incurable kidney disease left her with a litany of adverse symptoms.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t something like I can just take a pill and be better; I was going to have to deal with this my whole life,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lee, who earned agold medalin the individual all-around in Tokyo, told the New York Times in aninterviewpublished last month.  While Lee hasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t publicly shared the specifics of her condition \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cbecause it may change as her medical team learns more about her illness,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009das noted by TODAY,abnormal swelling, hot flashes, cold spells and headaches forced her to modify her training and begin intensive physical therapy. It was an ironic situation in the fullest sense \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 her physical prowess, what her worth had hinged upon as far as society was concerned, was at bitter odds with her body.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was like, who is this person looking back at me?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lee told The Times. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was so scary. I didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know it then, but the old Suni was gone. And she would never be back.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Sunisa Lee of Team United States on Balance Beam competes during the women's Artistic Gymnastics All-Around Final on day six of the Olympic Games Paris 2024 at Bercy Arena on August 01, 2024 in Paris, France. (Stefan Matzke \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 sampics/Getty Images)  Champions are made, not by pandering to the noise, but by believing in the fullest version of oneself.  Lee\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s case is only one instance of how invisible illnesses remain an unaddressed issue in athletics; oftentimes, interest and sympathy are only assigned to ailments that can be perceived outwardly. In a 2023column for Slate,\\u00c2\\u00a0Fortesa Latifi writes, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cChronic illness forces you to make a choice: look at your body differently, as something that is imperfect, or spend your entire life mourning what has been left behind in the land of health. For chronically ill athletes, it can be a tightrope walk to figure out how to push their bodies while respecting the limits of their diseases.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Oftentimes, there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a chasmic dissonance between the urge to fulfill societal expectations of the quintessential athlete and what can actually be accomplished while one\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s health flounders. As alongtime competitive runnerand chronically ill person, this is an experience I can speak to directly.  Lee however remained undeterred by her illness and summoned the gumption and self-confidence to return to the mat after a brief hiatus, brushing aside the narrowly construed frameworks of athleticism. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThis comeback was so much more than my return to elite gymnastics,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she wrote in a 2023 Instagrampost.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was me proving to myself that I can overcome hard things, and to hopefully inspire others to never let life\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s setbacks stop you from going after your dreams.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  https://www.instagram.com/p/CvnNv1TO648/?igshid=NTY1MGJiNDNiYw%3D%3D&img_index=1  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cMy doctor was telling me he didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t think I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099d be able to do gymnastics ever again,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lee shared with TODAY. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo to even be here is an accomplishment in itself. And I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m super proud of myself.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Then comes Richardson, the sprinting dynamo who saw her first shot at the Olympics dashed after testing positive for marijuana, leading to a 30-day suspension that saw her barred from Tokyo despite winning the 100-meter event at the trials. But to hear it in her own words, it was a\\u00c2\\u00a0 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cnerve triggering\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d event that Richardson said sent her spiraling.Speaking to NBCaround the time of her suspension, Richardson claimed she had used drugs to cope with learning of the death of her biological mother. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt sent me into a state of emotional panic,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know how to control my emotions or deal with my emotions during that time.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri Richardson (@itskerrii) joins us live for an exclusive interview to discuss the positive marijuana test that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s put her Olympic future in limbo.pic.twitter.com/iVBp3zhvja  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 TODAY (@TODAYshow)July 2, 2021    While Richardson did objectively violate rules set in place by U.S.A. Track & Field and International Olympic Committee, her penalty was cast into speculation when the Court of Arbitration for Sports (CAS) decided topermitRussianfigure skater Kamila Valievato compete after she tested positive for trimetazidine, a drug often used to treat heart conditions like angina.  \\\"Can we get a solid answer on the difference of her situation and mines?\\\" Richardsonwrote on a USA Today post,sharing the news that Valieva would be allowed to compete. \\\"My mother died, and I can not run and was also favored to place Top 3. The only difference I see is I am a Black young lady.\\\"  Call it an ambition fueled by being dealt a shady hand, but Richardson\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s experience seemed to have only emboldened her spirits as she sought to redeem her image. At the 2023 World Championships in Budapest, Richardson bested top Jamaican athletes Shericka Jackson and Shelly-Ann Fraser Pryce in the 100-meter dash, taking the win in a blistering 10.65 seconds. Afterward, she self-assuredly uttered the signature mantra she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s proclaimed repeatedly over the past year: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not back. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m better.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri Richardson: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not back I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m better\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009dpic.twitter.com/2iNR9VVeOP  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Travis Miller (@travismillerx13)July 8, 2023    Richardson elaborated on the saying in aninterview with Voguepublished last month. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t just mean I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m a better runner,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s beyond that. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m better at being Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m better at being myself.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s easy to perceive Olympians as athletes. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what they are, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what they do, and boy do they do it well. But lest we forget that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts, or that the parts extend far beyond the confines of athleticism alone. These redemption narratives speak to their achievements, but they also function to challenge (if not altogether reframe) the notion of what it means to be a great athlete \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 before they were Olympians, they were Simone, Sunisa and Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri.\\u00c2  This knowledge also allows us laypeople to find some comfort in compelling Olympic comeback tales. Perhaps the most honest yet hard-to-grapple-with truth about Olympians is that they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re quite like us \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 their inspiring stories serve as reminders of our own capabilities (albeit less coordinated ones), goading us to take the rarely invested time to reflect inward on what we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve accomplished in our own lives. Perhaps, they might even encourage us to hold our hearts and minds in kinder regard, refuting society\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prevailing disregard for mental health.\\u00c2  After winning the 100-meter dash final at the Stade de France, U.S. sprinterNoah Lylespublished a candidtweet:\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have Asthma, allergies, dyslexia, ADD, anxiety, and Depression. But I will tell you that what you have does not define what you can become. Why Not You!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Lyles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 message quite cloudlessly encapsulates the crux of the multifaceted elements of an athlete, of a human being \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 to become theworld\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s fastest man,he had to nurtureallof his needs, not simply fine-tune his physicality.\\u00c2  His remarks are also a steady reminder of the way disability, despite being an ostensible impediment, can be worked with while being exceptionally athletic. When the Olympics end this Sunday, the Paralympics will follow, commencing in Paris on Aug. 28. And if there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s something we can all take from watching para-Olympians compete, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s that champions are made, not by pandering to the noise, but by believing in the fullest version of oneself.\\u00c2  Read more  about the Olympics  \\u00c2  Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026 Salon.com, LLC. Reproduction of material from any Salon pages without written permission is strictly prohibited. SALON \\u00c2\\u00ae is registered in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office as a trademark of Salon.com, LLC. Associated Press articles: Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2016 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.  DMCA Policy  By subscribing, you agree that Salon will automatically charge you at the then-current rate (currently $9.95/month or $95/year) each month/year until you cancel. Log in to your account anytime to cancel prior to renewal date and avoid future charges.  Your current signup type is\"}"